The article discusses the significance of countering corruption as a core national security interest for the United States. It highlights the detrimental effects of corruption on public trust, governance, market distortion, development efforts, and democracy. The costs of corruption are estimated to be between 2 and 5 percent of global GDP. The article emphasizes the need to prevent and combat corruption, promote good governance, and bring transparency to financial systems. It also calls for holding corrupt individuals accountable, strengthening international institutions, supporting civil society and media, and partnering with other countries to counteract strategic corruption. The article directs the Assistant to the President and National Security Advisor to conduct an interagency review to develop a strategy to effectively combat corruption and improve governance. The review process will involve various agencies and offices, and its recommendations are expected to be submitted to the President within 200 days.